Two Types of Monitors in Citrix
In Citrix Systems (ADC / NetScaler), health checks are called Monitors.
They typically configure:
✔ TCP Monitor (Port Check)
Checks: server:port reachable
Example:
Plain text
Copy code
server1:8080
✔ HTTP Monitor (Application Check)
Checks: specific URL response
Example:
Plain text
Copy code
http://server1:8080/app1/health
⚙️ 2️⃣ How Citrix Team Implements (Step-by-Step)
Step 1 — Create HTTP Monitor
Citrix team creates a monitor like:
Plain text
Copy code
Type: HTTP
Send String: GET /app1/health HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: server1\r\n\r\n
Expected Response: 200 OK
Or simple config:
Plain text
Copy code
URL: /app1/health
Response Code: 200
Interval: 5 sec
Timeout: 3 sec
Step 2 — Bind Monitor to Service / Server
Each backend server (AppNode) is configured as a Service:
Plain text
Copy code
Service: server1:8080
Service: server2:8080
Then attach monitor:
Plain text
Copy code
bind service server1:8080 -monitorName app1_http_monitor
Step 3 — (Optional but Recommended) Combine TCP + HTTP
They can bind multiple monitors:
Plain text
Copy code
bind service server1:8080 -monitorName tcp_monitor
bind service server1:8080 -monitorName app1_http_monitor
Now health = both checks
🔄 3️⃣ Runtime Behavior
Citrix continuously checks:
Plain text
Copy code
Every 5 seconds →
   Call /app1/health
Result Handling:
Response
Citrix Action
200 OK
Server marked UP
404 / 500 / Timeout
Server marked DOWN
🧠 4️⃣ Important Logic (Very Key)
Citrix does NOT understand BW6 internally.
It only understands:
Plain text
Copy code
"If URL works → server healthy"
"If URL fails → server unhealthy"
So your health API becomes the truth.
